{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 20:02:37.371428", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nOverview\n- Topology: 4-tier Clos fabric using eBGP. Leaf routers advertise service subnets 10.<pod>.<idx>.0/24. One DNS (Bind) per pod; web servers serve HTTP on port 80. Clients in 192.168.<pod>.0/24 use pod DNS to resolve names.\n- Target pod: pod0, with dns_pod0 (10.0.0.2) and webserver0_pod0 (10.0.1.2). Client: client_0 (192.168.0.2).\n\nTests performed and key observations\n- Reachability and DNS:\n  - client_0 can ping dns_pod0 (10.0.0.2) and webserver0_pod0 (10.0.1.2) with low RTTs.\n  - /etc/resolv.conf on client_0 lists nameserver 10.0.0.2 and 10.1.0.2.\n  - dig from client_0 resolves web0.pod0 to 10.0.1.2 (correct).\n- HTTP service:\n  - On webserver0_pod0, port 80 is listening (python http server): netstat shows 0.0.0.0:80 LISTEN.\n  - From dns_pod0, HTTP to 10.0.1.2 returns quickly (curl timings small), indicating the web server is healthy intra-fabric.\n  - From client_0, ad-hoc curl HTTP code output showed 000 (indicates connection not established/response not received). Note: the timing-only curl tests from client_0 reported very small totals; however, the explicit HTTP code checks returned 000, suggesting a connectivity/forwarding issue specific to client_0’s path.\n- Path tests:\n  - traceroute from client_0 to 10.0.1.2 shows 192.168.0.1 (super spine) then destination, consistent with 2 L3 hops observed (interpretation limited by simulation, but L3 reachability exists).\n- BGP/forwarding state:\n  - All BGP sessions across super spine, spines, and leaves are Established; no neighbor drops observed (show ip bgp summary on all routers).\n  - super_spine_router_0 RIB has:\n    - 10.0.1.0/24 via all spines (ECMP).\n    - Unexpected more-specific 10.0.1.0/25 learned via 172.16.0.3 (spine_router_0_1) and selected as best.\n  - spine_router_0_1 configuration:\n    - interface lo ip address 10.0.1.0/25\n    - router bgp 65101 … address-family: network 10.0.1.0/25\n    - show ip route 10.0.1.0/25: “Known via connected, directly connected, lo”\n  - leaf_router_0_1 correctly originates 10.0.1.0/24.\n\nAnomalies detected\n1) Route hijack of 10.0.1.0/25 by a spine\n   - In this Clos design, only leaves should originate service subnets, and they should be /24 prefixes (10.<pod>.<idx>.0/24). A spine should not own or advertise a more-specific service prefix.\n   - spine_router_0_1 has a loopback set to 10.0.1.0/25 and advertises 10.0.1.0/25 into BGP. This is a misconfiguration that conflicts with the leaf’s 10.0.1.0/24.\n   - super_spine_router_0 installs the /25 as best for 10.0.1.0–10.0.1.127, overriding the intended /24 path to the leaf.\n\n2) Potential inconsistent forwarding/blackholing for traffic in 10.0.1.0/25\n   - Packets to 10.0.1.2 (within the hijacked /25) will prefer the spine_router_0_1 path due to longest-prefix match.\n   - On spine_router_0_1, 10.0.1.0/25 is “connected” via lo. This is not a real external interface; the kernel considers the subnet on-lo, which cannot forward to the actual host at 10.0.1.2 behind the leaf.\n   - This situation commonly leads to traffic being dropped or mishandled at the spine for those destinations, depending on kernel behavior.\n   - Symptoms align: client_0’s HTTP to 10.0.1.2 shows failures (HTTP code 000), while intra-fabric HTTP (from dns_pod0) works. ICMP pings may still succeed due to differences in path selection or measurement effects, but TCP traffic is affected in practice from the client path.\n\nFault localization\n- Primary faulty device: spine_router_0_1\n  - Misconfigured loopback IP 10.0.1.0/25 and BGP advertisement of 10.0.1.0/25.\n- Secondary propagation: super_spine_router_0\n  - Correctly installs and propagates the more-specific /25 received from spine_router_0_1, causing the hijack to affect all upstream traffic targeting 10.0.1.0/25 addresses.\n\nRoot cause\n- Configuration error on spine_router_0_1:\n  - A service subnet more-specific (10.0.1.0/25) is assigned to the spine’s loopback and advertised via BGP. This violates the fabric’s routing policy (leaves advertise /24 service subnets) and causes the super spine and the rest of the fabric to prefer the incorrect /25 path, diverting traffic away from the correct leaf and potentially blackholing it on the spine.\n\nRelevant evidence\n- spine_router_0_1 running-config shows:\n  - interface lo ip address 10.0.1.0/25\n  - router bgp 65101 … address-family: network 10.0.1.0/25\n- spine_router_0_1: show ip route 10.0.1.0/25 → directly connected via lo.\n- super_spine_router_0: show ip bgp 10.0.1.0/25 → best path via 172.16.0.3 (spine_router_0_1).\n- leaf_router_0_1 correctly originates 10.0.1.0/24.\n- client_0 DNS resolves web0.pod0 to 10.0.1.2; ICMP reachability is present; HTTP from client_0 reports failures (HTTP code 000), while intra-fabric HTTP tests succeed.\n\nAssessment of network health\n- Control plane: BGP adjacencies are up and stable across tiers.\n- Data plane: Incorrect more-specific route advertisement from a spine introduces a traffic hijack for half of the pod0 web subnet (10.0.1.0/25), producing inconsistent behavior for flows sourced from external clients (observed HTTP failures) and risking blackholing for all destinations in that range.\n- DNS and services: DNS is functioning; web service is up on the server; the failure is due to the routing anomaly rather than service or DNS issues.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 17059, "output_tokens": 6496, "total_tokens": 23555, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 16384}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 4928}}}
